1. Introduction\par
\par
    Improving mechanical properties of crystalline metallic materials has been one of the eternal pursuits in materials sci-\par
ence. In recent years, plaini\u64257?cation has been proposed to provide crystalline metallic materials with high strength and ex-\par
cellent ductility without changing the chemical composition (Li and Lu, 2019). For example, nanocrystalline metals with\par
bimodal microstructures (Wang et al., 2002), nanotwinned materials (Lu et al., 2009) and gradient structure materials\par
(Lin et al., 2018) are three successful cases, in which excellent mechanical properties are achieved by controlling microstruc-\par
tures and spatial distribution of grain boundaries (GBs). From a microscopic perspective, the interaction between dislocations\par
and GBs, including dislocation transmission across GBs (Bieler et al., 2019; Guo et al., 2015; Lee et al., 1990) and activation\par
of dislocation sources in adjacent grains (Bayerschen et al., 2016; Cottrell, 1958; Gen\u233?e et al., 2017), shall play an important\par
role in affecting the mechanical behaviors and properties of crystalline metallic materials, which could further assist crack\par
initiation (Li et al., 2013; Shanthraj and Zikry, 2013; Zhang and Wang, 2003), crack propagation (Chen et al., 2017; Wilson\par
et al., 2018), and cavity nucleation (Lim, 1989; Yoo and Trinkaus, 1986).\par
    It is well known that the dislocation-GB interaction is regulated by the stress concentration arising from dislocation pile-\par
ups, whose formation is caused by GBs hindering the motion of dislocations (Ding et al., 2016; Gemperlov\u225? et al., 2002;\par
Hirth and Lothe, 1982; Hull et al., 2011), and has been theoretically analyzed. For example, Eshelby et al. (1951) established\par
a discrete dislocation model to analyze the dislocation distribution in a pile-up. However, a lack of analytical solutions from\par
that discrete model limits its applications in scienti\u64257?c and engineering studies. Later on, a continuum model has been pro-\par
posed (Hirth and Lothe, 1982; Leibfried, 1951), from which analytical solutions of the dislocation distribution and stress\par
concentration in the dislocation pile-up have been derived. These analytical solutions are further veri\u64257?ed by the dislocation\par
dynamics (DD) simulations (Quek et al., 2014). The dislocation-GB interaction is also closely related to the misorientation\par
between two adjacent grains (Shen et al., 1986; 1988). As an important mechanism of dislocation-GB interaction, the dis-\par
location transmission has been a continuous focus of interest for mechanical engineers and material scientists. Nowadays,\par
there are two mostly used empirical methods to qualitatively assess the role of microstructures in dislocation transmission.\par
One is the plastic compatibility factor developed by Luster and Morris (1995) taking into account the spatial information\par
of slip systems. The larger the plastic compatibility factor is, the easier the dislocation transmission could occur. The other\par
method is based on the LRB criteria established by Lee et al. (1989), that is, (1) the misorientation angle between the slip\par
planes should be minimized; (2) the resolved shear stress (RSS) on the outgoing slip system arising from the dislocation\par
pile-up should be maximized; (3) the magnitude of the Burgers vector of residual dislocation should be minimized. Al-\par
though both methods provide convenient and effective assessment of the likelihood of dislocation transmission (Bayerschen\par
et al., 2016; Han et al., 2018; H\u233?mery et al., 2018; Kacher et al., 2014), the related micro-mechanism was veiled because\par
only qualitative analysis can be performed. Currently, further explorations with molecular dynamics (MD) studies (Adlakha\par
and Solanki, 2016; Sangid et al., 2011; Tsuru et al., 2009) and DD simulations (Kapoor and Verdhan, 2017; Li et al., 2009; Liu\par
et al., 2012; Lu et al., 2019) provided physical insight into the dislocation transmission and revealed the role of GB interfa-\par
cial energy in regulating the dislocation transmission. Though the dislocation transmission has been extensively studied, it\par
remains challenging to quantitatively assess the dislocation transmission at various GB misorientation angles and clarify its\par
role in affecting the yield strength of crystalline metals.\par
    In addition to dislocation transmission across GBs, dislocation pile-ups could lead to the activation of dislocation sources\par
in adjacent grains to assist plastic deformation of polycrystals (Cottrell, 1958; Davis et al., 1966; H\u233?mery et al., 2018; Joseph\par
et al., 2018). Experiments have shown that the adjacent grains undergo serious plastic deformation even in the absence\par
of dislocation transmission (Gen\u233?e et al., 2017; Joseph et al., 2018), indicating that the dislocation sources are certainly\par
activated in adjacent grains. Due to the dislocation pile-up, the stress by superposition of Peach\u8211?Koehler forces can activate\par
the dislocation source in adjacent grains (Guo et al., 2014; Hirth and Lothe, 1982; Quek et al., 2014). The model proposed by\par
Livingston and Chalmers (1957) has been applied to calculate the projected stress on the outgoing slip system arising from\par
the dislocation pile-up in one slip system. However, that model is insu\u64259?cient to describe the behavior of dislocation source\par
activation (Davis et al., 1966), and the quantitative relation between critical activation stress and GB misorientation angles\par
is not established yet.\par
    In this study, a theoretical framework taking into account both dislocation transmission and dislocation source activation\par
is established to investigate the underlying physics of the dislocation-GB interaction. The critical stress of dislocation trans-\par
mission is formulated based on the energy release rate during the dislocation pile-up formation and the energy barrier for\par
dislocation transmission. Moreover, dislocation source activation for multiple slip systems is characterized by incorporating\par
the Frank-Read (FR) source model (Foreman, 1967). It is found that the activation of dislocation sources is sensitive to the\par
loading direction, consistent with recent experimental results (Gen\u233?e et al., 2017). Finally, the comparison of critical stresses\par
between the dislocation transmission and the dislocation source activation is performed at low angle GB (LAGB) and high\par
angle GB (HAGB). Our results help to improve the understanding of the dislocation pile-up based dislocation-GB interac-\par
tion and provide the corresponding quantitative descriptions to assist rational design of metallic materials with excellent\par
mechanical properties.\par
    The remainder of this paper is organized as follows. In Section 2, the dislocation pile-up is modelled and types of\par
dislocation-GB interaction are introduced. In Section 3, the residual dislocation tensor is introduced and the critical stress\par
of dislocation transmission is determined from an energy-based method. In Section 4, the activation of dislocation sources\par
in adjacent grains is studied under single and multiple slip dislocation pile-ups. Theoretical results are presented to de-\par
