\par
2.2. Dislocation-GB interaction\par
\par
   Experimental observations suggest that the underlying mechanism of dislocation-GB interaction consists of dislocation\par
transmission and dislocation source activation (Bayerschen et al., 2016), and three situations might exist as shown in Fig. 2.\par
As the dislocation transmits across the GB, the dislocation pile-up could be relaxed (Haouala et al., 2020), which means\par
that the stress concentration near the GB would not be further strengthened. Therefore, the occurrence of dislocation trans-\par
mission is unfavorable to the activation of dislocation source in adjacent grains. This deduction is consistent with statistical\par
experimental results that dislocation transmission mostly occurs at LAGB, and dislocation source activation is more likely\par
to occur at HAGB (Bayerschen et al., 2016; Gen\u233?e et al., 2017; H\u233?mery et al., 2018). In the following sections, we introduce\par
how to determine the critical stress required for the occurrence of these situations based on the dislocation pile-up model.\par
