3.2. Residual dislocation tensor\par
\par
    It has been proposed that the smaller the magnitude of the Burgers vector of residual dislocation | b| = |bA \u8722? bB | is\par
(subscripts A and B denote the grains A and B, respectively), the easier the dislocation transmission is (Abuzaid et al., 2012;\par
Gurtin, 2008; Han et al., 2018; Lee et al., 1989; 1990; Li et al., 2009; Sch\u228?fer et al., 2016). However, in some cases the\par
magnitude of b is insu\u64259?cient to assess the dislocation transmission behaviors. For example, Shen et al. (1986) found that\par
the angle between the line of intersection of slip planes in grains A and B and the GB plane should be as small as possible\par
for dislocation transmission, meaning that the misorientation of slip planes between grains A and B provides an energy\par
barrier for dislocation transmission (H\u233?mery et al., 2018). To establish the theoretical description of that energy barrier for\par
dislocation transmission, here the dislocation transmissions are categorized into three types as follows and illustrated in\par
Fig. 3.\par
\par
(1) At b = 0 and nA \u215? nB = 0, the leading dislocation can directly transfer to the adjacent grain with zero energy barrier\par
    (Ebarrier = 0).\par
(2) In the case of b = 0 or nA \u215? nB = 0, the dislocations on both sides of a GB are incompatible. Thus the GB would\par
    prohibit the dislocation transmission. The dislocation transmits across the GB in a manner of GB absorbing an incoming\par
    dislocation followed by emitting an outgoing dislocation (Han et al., 2018).\par
(3) At bA \u183? nGB = 0, the dislocations do not transmit across the GB, and Ebarrier = 0.\par
\par
    Here b and n represent the Burgers vector and the unit normal vectors of slip plane, respectively, and can be determined\par
by coordinate transformation matrices from crystal coordinate system to sample frames (see Appendix). The subscripts A, B\par
and GB refer to quantities pertaining to the grains A, B and GB, respectively. One can \u64257?nd that the dislocation transmission\par
is closely associated with spatial relations between the incoming slip system, outgoing slip system and GB plane, and these\par
relations play essential roles in quantitative studies of the critical stress of dislocation transmission.\par
    An edge dislocation is considered as an extra half-plane of atoms [Fig. 3(b)], which can further be characterized by the\par
normal directions of atomic plane (bA and bB ) and plane-in vectors (nA and nB ) (Hull et al., 2011). The difference between\par
dislocations on incoming and outgoing slip systems can also be characterized by these four vectors. A residual dislocation\par
tensor beff can be obtained to satisfy the conservation law of lattice defect during the dislocation transmission (symbol \par
denoting the tensor product) as\par
\par
