5. Numerical results of dislocation transmission\par
\par
    The developed theoretical model is employed to study the dislocation transmission behaviors. Firstly, the outgoing slip\par
systems are predicted and compared with experimental results of stainless steels (in Section 5.1) (Cui et al., 2014; Lee et al.,\par
1989). Secondly, the effect of GB misorientation angle \u952? on critical transmission stress \u964? ct is discussed in Section 5.2. Finally,\par
\u964? ct displays a dependence on grain size D in Section 5.3.\par
\par
5.1. Predictions of outgoing slip systems\par
\par
    Taking FCC materials as an example, the critical transmission stress \u964? ct [Eq. (3.14)] of the preferential outgoing slip system\par
corresponds to the smallest \u964? ct among the 12 slip systems. Then it can also be inferred that the secondary outgoing slip\par
system has the second smallest \u964? ct . Accordingly, activation behaviors of outgoing slip systems can be predicted by comparing\par
the corresponding \u964? ct .\par
    Theoretical predictions [Eq. (3.14)] are compared with the experimental data of 310 stainless steel (Lee et al., 1989) and\par
304 stainless steel (Cui et al., 2014). According to Eqs. (3.12) and (3.14), the critical transmission stress \u964? ct for a \u64257?xed GB is\par
only associated with the magnitude of residual dislocation tensor beff . Thus the factor beff /b can be used to evaluate the\par
activation behaviors of outgoing slip systems, i.e. the smaller the factor beff /b is, the easier the dislocation transmission\par
becomes.\par
    Experimental results and theoretical predictions of \u64257?ve groups of dislocation transmissions are presented in Table 1. It\par
can be seen that the slip system with the smallest value of beff /b is activated preferentially. Moreover, in the second group\par
experimental data, the activation of the secondary outgoing slip system has the second smallest beff /b, which veri\u64257?es the\par
validity of our model. Meanwhile, in the \u64257?fth group of the experimental data, Cui et al. (2014) found that the outgoing slip\par
