   It is well known that the yield stress of polycrystalline materials displays the Hall-Petch effect (Hall, 1951; Li et al., 2009;\par
Petch, 1953), i.e. the yield stress \u963? y increases with decreasing grain size D (\u963?y \u8733? D\u8722?0.5 ). In this study, such an effect can be\par
further interpreted by the decreasing energy release rate with decreasing D [Eq. (2.6)]. According to Eq. (3.14), the evolution\par
of \u964? ct ~ D at different \u952? is investigated. Here the incoming slip system is \u64257?xed as [11\u772?0](111 ), and nGB is set as (11\u772?0 ).\par
   \u964? ct at \u952? = 5o , 15o , 25o and 35o display the Hall-Petch effect (Fig. 11). As \u952? decreases, the Hall-Petch effect becomes\par
weaker, consistent with the simulation results by Li et al. (2009) that the Hall-Petch effect with HAGB is more apparent\par
than that with LAGB. As shown in the inset of Fig. 11, our theoretical model shows good agreement with DD simulations\par
(Kapoor and Verdhan, 2017). The LAGB investigated by DD simulations is composed of a series of edge dislocations with\par
spacing of S = 80b (Kapoor and Verdhan, 2017), and its misorientation angle can thus be approximated as \u952? = b/S \u8776? 0.72o\par
(Hirth and Lothe, 1982). As the dislocation motion resistance \u964? 0 was not considered in DD simulations, \u964?0 = 0 MPa is taken\par
in our theoretical analysis.\par
