6. Numerical results of dislocation source activation\par
\par
    The dislocation pile-up induced dislocation source activations in adjacent grains is investigated in this section. Using\par
Eq. (2.7), the shear stress \u64257?eld \u964? xy /\u964? eff ahead of the dislocation pile-up is plotted in Fig. 12 as a function of xGB = x \u8722? D/2.\par
The stress concentration exists in the region near the GB and gradually vanishes as xGB increases, veri\u64257?ed by experiments\par
(Britton and Wilkinson, 2012; Guo et al., 2014). Under the stress concentration, dislocation sources with activation stress\par
less than local stress can be activated (Cottrell, 1958; Joseph et al., 2018). Here the bi-crystal Al (see Fig. 7) is taken as an\par
example for investigation, and tilt GBs with \u952? from 0o to 90o are considered. According to the experimental observations\par
(Gen\u233?e et al., 2017; Joseph et al., 2018), the distance from the dislocation nucleation site or the core of plastic zone to GBs\par
falls in a range from around several hundred nanometers to several micrometers, and the average grain size ranges from\par
around 4 \u956?m to 350 \u956?m. Therefore, we adopt the source distance of 1 \u956?m for a grain size of 10 \u956?m, as listed in Table 2.\par
