we analyze the ratio of critical stresses \u963? ct /\u963? cs . \u963? cs and \u963? ct are determined from Eqs. (4.9) and (5.2), respectively. Material\par
parameters are listed in Table 2, and nGB =(012). Two loading directions [010] and [001] are selected.\par
     Fig. 15 displays \u963? ct /\u963? cs with various \u952? and xs . As xs increases, \u963? ct /\u963? cs decreases, consistent with Fig. 12 showing that\par
the stress ahead of the dislocation pile-up decreases with increasing distance from GB. The FR source far away from GB\par
is di\u64259?cult to be activated, and thus the plastic zone induced by dislocation pile-ups forms near GB as shown in Fig. 2.\par
\u963? ct /\u963? cs increases as \u952? increases from 0o to 45o , meaning that the dislocation transmission is easier to occur at LAGB, but\par
FR source activation is prone to occur at HAGB. The underlying physical reasons are that, the dislocation transmission across\par
LAGB suffers small resistance, and the dislocation pile-up can be relaxed and there would not be enough stress to activate\par
the dislocation source. However, the HAGB provides a high resistance for dislocation transmission, leading to signi\u64257?cant\par
dislocation pile-ups and dislocation source activations. It is noted that this conclusion is only valid for 100 tilt GBs. For\par
certain GBs with low interfacial energy, the dislocation-GB interactions could be more affected by EGB than \u952? (Sangid et al.,\par
2011).\par
     The contour plots of \u963? ct /\u963? cs are shown in Figs. 15(b) and (d). At \u963? ct /\u963? cs > 1, activation of FR source dominates\par
dislocation-GB interactions. At \u963? ct /\u963? cs \u8776? 1, FR source activation and dislocation transmission can occur simultaneously as\par
observed in experiments (see Fig. 2) (Gen\u233?e et al., 2017). At \u963? ct /\u963? cs < 1, dislocation transmission prevails. In addition,\par
\u963? ct /\u963? cs in the loading direction [010] is smaller than that in the loading direction [001], which means that the source acti-\par
vation further away from GB can be activated under the loading direction [001]. Although the FR source activation is sen-\par
sitive to the loading direction, the activation behavior under different loading directions still does not occur at very small\par
\u952? due to the relaxation of dislocation pile-ups during dislocation transmission, which is consistent with the experimental\par
observations (Gen\u233?e et al., 2017; Joseph et al., 2018).\par
     Finally, the relation between three factors proposed in LRB criteria (Lee et al., 1989; 1990) and dislocation-GB interac-\par
tions can be clari\u64257?ed. Overall, the misorientation angle between the incoming and outgoing slip planes and the residual\par
dislocation can equally affect the energy barrier for dislocation transmission. However, the RSS on the outgoing slip system\par
arising from the dislocation pile-up dominates the activation of dislocation sources in adjacent grains. In this study, the ef-\par
fects of residual stress, local differences in statistical strength, non-uniform inter- and intragranular mechanical \u64257?elds on the\par
dislocation-GB interaction are not considered, which in certain cases might play collective roles in affecting the dislocation-\par
GB interaction. A thorough and cross-scale theoretical modeling considering these factors is challenging and deserves further\par
dedicated investigations with incorporation of crystal plasticity \u64257?nite element method.\par
\par
7. Conclusions\par
\par
    In this work, a theoretical model is developed to study the dislocation-grain boundary (GB) interaction with focus on the\par
dislocation transmission and dislocation source activation. This model not only quantitatively describes the microstructure-\par
\par
                                                                               15\par
W. Liu, Y. Liu, H. Sui et al.                                                      Journal of the Mechanics and Physics of Solids 145 (2020) 104158\par
\par
\par
related dislocation-GB interaction, but also clari\u64257?es the misorientation angle-dependent competition relation between dis-\par
location transmission and dislocation source activation. Speci\u64257?cally, the energy released from the end of dislocation pile-\par
up goes over the energy barrier characterized by the residual dislocation tensor and GB energy to drive the dislocation\par
transmission across GB. Based on the residual dislocation tensor, the critical transmission stress can be connected with the\par
phenomenological plastic compatibility factor. In addition, critical stress that activates Frank-Read (FR) sources in adjacent\par
grains is examined by evaluating the local stress ahead of the dislocation pile-up. In contrast to the formulation of single\par
slip dislocation pile-up, a more realistic formulation of multiple slip dislocation pile-ups is proposed to investigate the ac-\par
tivation behaviors of dislocation source, in which the contribution of all incoming slip systems is taken into account in the\par
calculation of the stress on FR source.\par
    100 tilt GBs are taken as examples to systematically study the dislocation-GB interaction. Main conclusions are sum-\par
marized as follows.\par
\par
(1) The quantitative analysis shows that with increasing misorientation angle, the critical stress of dislocation transmission\par
    increases, which also displays the dependence of grain size. In addition, the model accurately predicts the activation of\par
    primary and secondary outgoing slip systems observed in reported experiments.\par
(2) Critical stress of dislocation source activation is quantitatively analyzed for single and multiple slip dislocation pile-ups.\par
    Compared with single slip system, the result of multiple slip systems shows lower critical activation stress and loading\par
    direction sensitivity, interpreting the reported results of dislocation source activation in polycrystals.\par
(3) Comparing the activation stresses of dislocation transmission and dislocation source activation for 100 tilt GBs, the\par
    dislocation transmission dominates dislocation-GB interaction at low angle GB, whereas the dislocation source activation\par
    is more likely to occur at high angle GB.\par
